<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AHP_TDHLeadImage.png" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c=
a/AHP_TDHLeadImage.png/250px-AHP_TDHLeadImage.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"262" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"567" d=
ata-file-height=3D"595"></a><figcaption>A simple AHP hierarchy, with final =
priorities. The goal is to select the most suitable leader from a field of =
three candidates. The factors to be considered are experience, education, c=
harisma, and age. According to the judgments of the decision makers, Dick i=
s the strongest candidate, followed by Tom, then Harry. Their decision proc=
ess is described in depth in an appendix to this article.</figcaption></fig=
ure>
<p>In the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_makin=
g" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decision making">decision making</a>, the=
 <b>analytic hierarchy process</b> (<b>AHP</b>), also <b>analytical hierarc=
hy process</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FormanGass_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-F=
ormanGass-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> is a structured technique for organizing and analyz=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MCDA" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"MCDA">complex decisions</a>, based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychology" title=3D"Psychology">psycholo=
gy</a>. It was developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas=
_L._Saaty" title=3D"Thomas L. Saaty">Thomas L. Saaty</a> in the 1970s; Saat=
y partnered with Ernest Forman to develop <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Expert_Choice" title=3D"Expert Choice">Expert Choice</a></i> sof=
tware in 1983, and AHP has been extensively studied and refined since then.=
 It represents an accurate approach to quantifying the weights of decision =
criteria. Individual <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expert" title=
=3D"Expert">experts</a>=E2=80=99 experiences are utilized to estimate the r=
elative magnitudes of factors through pair-wise comparisons. Each of the re=
spondents compares the relative importance of each pair of items using a sp=
ecially designed questionnaire. The relative importance of the criteria can=
 be determined with the help of the AHP by comparing the criteria and, if a=
pplicable, the sub-criteria in pairs by experts or decision-makers. On this=
 basis, the best alternative can be found.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Uses_and_applications">Uses=
 and applications</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=
=3D"Edit section: Uses and applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>AHP is targeted at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_decisi=
on_making" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Group decision making">group deci=
sion making</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GDM_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-GDM-2">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> and is used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decisio=
n_making" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decision making">decision situatio=
ns</a>, in fields such as government, business, industry,<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_=
hierarchy_process#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> healthcare and education.=20
</p><p>Rather than prescribing a "correct" decision, the AHP helps decision=
 makers find the decision that best suits their goal and their understandin=
g of the problem. It provides a comprehensive and rational framework for st=
ructuring a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_problem" titl=
e=3D"Decision problem">decision problem</a>, for representing and quantifyi=
ng its elements, for relating those elements to overall goals, and for eval=
uating alternative solutions.
</p><p>Users of the AHP first decompose their decision problem into a hiera=
rchy of more easily comprehended sub-problems, each of which can be analyze=
d independently. The elements of the hierarchy can relate to any aspect of =
the decision problem=E2=80=94tangible or intangible, carefully measured or =
roughly estimated, well or poorly understood=E2=80=94anything at all that a=
pplies to the decision at hand.
</p><p>Once the hierarchy is built, the decision makers evaluate its variou=
s elements by comparing them to each other two at a time, with respect to t=
heir impact on an element above them in the hierarchy. In making the compar=
isons, the decision makers can use concrete data about the elements, and th=
ey can also use their judgments about the elements' relative meaning and im=
portance. Human judgments, and not just the underlying information, can be =
used in performing the evaluations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-RACSAM_4-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_pro=
cess#cite_note-RACSAM-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The AHP converts these evaluations to numerical values that can be p=
rocessed and compared over the entire range of the problem. A numerical wei=
ght or <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/priority" class=3D"extiw" =
title=3D"wikt:priority">priority</a> is derived for each element of the hie=
rarchy, allowing diverse and often incommensurable elements to be compared =
to one another in a rational and consistent way. This capability distinguis=
hes the AHP from other decision making techniques.
</p><p>In the final step of the process, numerical priorities are calculate=
d for each of the decision alternatives. These numbers represent the altern=
atives' relative ability to achieve the decision goal, so they allow a stra=
ightforward consideration of the various courses of action.
</p><p>While it can be used by individuals working on straightforward decis=
ions, the Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) is most useful where teams of pe=
ople are working on complex problems, especially those with high stakes, in=
volving human perceptions and judgments, whose resolutions have long-term r=
epercussions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bhushan,_2004_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-=
Bhushan,_2004-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Decision situations to which the AHP can be applied include:<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FormanGass_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-FormanGass-1"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<ul><li>Choice =E2=80=93 The selection of one alternative from a given set =
of alternatives, usually where there are multiple decision criteria involve=
d.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranking" title=3D"Ranking">Ran=
king</a> =E2=80=93 Putting a set of alternatives in order from most to leas=
t desirable.</li>
<li>Prioritization =E2=80=93 Determining the relative merit of members of a=
 set of alternatives, as opposed to selecting a single one or merely rankin=
g them</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resource_allocation" title=3D"=
Resource allocation">Resource allocation</a> =E2=80=93 Apportioning resourc=
es among a set of alternatives</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benchmarking" title=3D"Benchma=
rking">Benchmarking</a> =E2=80=93 Comparing the processes in one's own orga=
nization with those of other best-of-breed organizations</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quality_management" title=3D"Q=
uality management">Quality management</a> =E2=80=93 Dealing with the multid=
imensional aspects of quality and quality improvement</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conflict_resolution" title=3D"=
Conflict resolution">Conflict resolution</a> =E2=80=93 Settling disputes be=
tween parties with apparently incompatible goals or positions<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-GDM_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-GDM-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>The applications of AHP include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Planning" title=3D"Planning">planning</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Resource_allocation" title=3D"Resource allocation">resource alloc=
ation</a>, priority setting, and selection among alternatives.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Bhushan,_2004_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-Bhushan,_2004-5"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Other areas have included <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreca=
sting" title=3D"Forecasting">forecasting</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Total_quality_management" title=3D"Total quality management">to=
tal quality management</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Busine=
ss_process_reengineering" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Business process r=
eengineering">business process reengineering</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Quality_function_deployment" title=3D"Quality function depl=
oyment">quality function deployment</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Balanced_scorecard" title=3D"Balanced scorecard">balanced sc=
orecard</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FormanGass_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-Form=
anGass-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> Other uses of AHP are discussed in the literature:
</p>
<ul><li>Deciding how best to reduce the impact of global <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change" title=3D"Climate change">climate cha=
nge</a> (<i>Fondazione Eni Enrico Mattei</i>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_=
process#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantification_(science)" titl=
e=3D"Quantification (science)">Quantifying</a> the overall <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quality_(business)" title=3D"Quality (business)">q=
uality</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_system" tit=
le=3D"Software system">software systems</a> (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Corporation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Microso=
ft Corporation">Microsoft Corporation</a></i>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSDN_7-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hier=
archy_process#cite_note-MSDN-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Selecting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faculty_(teaching_st=
aff)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Faculty (teaching staff)">university f=
aculty</a> (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloomsburg_Universi=
ty_of_Pennsylvania" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bloomsburg University of=
 Pennsylvania">Bloomsburg University of Pennsylvania</a></i>)<sup id=3D"cit=
