>, <i>Wildfire Management to Help Mitigate Global Warming</i>, and <i>Rural=
 Microprojects in Nepal</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use">Use</h2><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Use"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AHPDevice.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description">=
<img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/AHPDe=
vice.jpg/250px-AHPDevice.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"150" height=3D"19=
7" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"400" data-file-height=3D"52=
5"></a><figcaption>A typical device for entering judgments in an AHP group =
decision making session</figcaption></figure><p>As it can be seen in the ma=
terial that follows, using the AHP involves the mathematical synthesis of n=
umerous judgments about the decision problem at hand. It is not uncommon fo=
r these judgments to number in the dozens or even the hundreds. While the m=
ath can be done by hand or with a calculator, it is far more common to use =
one of several computerized methods for entering and synthesizing the judgm=
ents. The simplest of these involve standard spreadsheet software, while th=
e most complex use custom software, often augmented by special devices for =
acquiring the judgments of decision makers gathered in a meeting room.
</p><p>The procedure for using the AHP can be summarized as:
</p>
<ol><li>Model the problem as a hierarchy containing the decision goal, the =
alternatives for reaching it, and the criteria for evaluating the alternati=
ves.</li>
<li>Establish priorities among the elements of the hierarchy by making a se=
ries of judgments based on pairwise comparisons of the elements. For exampl=
e, when comparing potential purchases of commercial real estate, the invest=
ors might say they prefer location over price and price over timing.</li>
<li>Synthesize these judgments to yield a set of overall priorities for the=
 hierarchy. This would combine the investors' judgments about location, pri=
ce and timing for properties A, B, C, and D into overall priorities for eac=
h property.</li>
<li>Check the consistency of the judgments.</li>
<li>Come to a final decision based on the results of this process.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-DMFL_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-DMFL-25"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></o=
l>
<p>These steps are more fully described below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Model_the_problem_as_a_hier=
archy">Model the problem as a hierarchy</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Model the problem as a hierarchy"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>The first step in the analytic hierarchy process is to model the problem=
 as a hierarchy. In doing this, participants explore the aspects of the pro=
blem at levels from general to detailed, then express it in the multilevele=
d way that the AHP requires. As they work to build the hierarchy, they incr=
ease their understanding of the problem, of its context, and of each other'=
s thoughts and feelings about both.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DMFL_25-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_proc=
ess#cite_note-DMFL-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Hierarchies_defined">Hierar=
chies defined</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"E=
dit section: Hierarchies defined"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A hierarchy is a stratified system of ranking and organizing people, thi=
ngs, ideas, etc., where each element of the system, except for the top one,=
 is subordinate to one or more other elements. Though the concept of hierar=
chy is easily grasped intuitively, it can also be described mathematically.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Principia_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-Principia-26"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Diagrams of hierarchies are often shaped roughly like pyramids, b=
ut other than having a single element at the top, there is nothing necessar=
ily pyramid-shaped about a hierarchy.
</p><p>Human organizations are often structured as hierarchies, where the h=
ierarchical system is used for assigning responsibilities, exercising leade=
rship, and facilitating communication. Familiar hierarchies of "things" inc=
lude a desktop computer's tower unit at the "top", with its subordinate mon=
itor, keyboard, and mouse "below."
</p><p>In the world of ideas, we use hierarchies to help us acquire detaile=
d knowledge of complex reality: we structure the reality into its constitue=
nt parts, and these in turn into their own constituent parts, proceeding do=
wn the hierarchy as many levels as we care to. At each step, we focus on un=
derstanding a single component of the whole, temporarily disregarding the o=
ther components at this and all other levels. As we go through this process=
, we increase our global understanding of whatever complex reality we are s=
tudying.
</p><p>Think of the hierarchy that medical students use while learning anat=
omy=E2=80=94they separately consider the musculoskeletal system (including =
parts and subparts like the hand and its constituent muscles and bones), th=
e circulatory system (and its many levels and branches), the nervous system=
 (and its numerous components and subsystems), etc., until they've covered =
all the systems and the important subdivisions of each. Advanced students c=
ontinue the subdivision all the way to the level of the cell or molecule. I=
n the end, the students understand the "big picture" and a considerable num=
ber of its details. Not only that, but they understand the relation of the =
individual parts to the whole. By working hierarchically, they've gained a =
comprehensive understanding of anatomy.
</p><p>Similarly, when we approach a complex decision problem, we can use a=
 hierarchy to integrate large amounts of information into our understanding=
 of the situation. As we build this information structure, we form a better=
 and better picture of the problem as a whole.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DMFL_25-2=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hie=
rarchy_process#cite_note-DMFL-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Hierarchies_in_the_AHP">Hie=
rarchies in the AHP</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=
=3D"Edit section: Hierarchies in the AHP"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>An AHP hierarchy is a structured means of modeling the decision at hand.=
 It consists of an overall goal, a group of options or alternatives for rea=
ching the goal, and a group of factors or criteria that relate the alternat=
ives to the goal. The criteria can be further broken down into subcriteria,=
 sub-subcriteria, and so on, in as many levels as the problem requires. A c=
riterion may not apply uniformly, but may have graded differences like a li=
ttle sweetness is enjoyable but too much sweetness can be harmful. In that =
case, the criterion is divided into subcriteria indicating different intens=
ities of the criterion, like: little, medium, high and these intensities ar=
e prioritized through comparisons under the parent criterion, sweetness.
Published descriptions of AHP applications often include diagrams and descr=
iptions of their hierarchies; some simple ones are shown throughout this ar=
ticle. More complex AHP hierarchies have been collected and reprinted in at=
 least one book.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hierarchon_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note=
-Hierarchon-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> More complex hierarchies can be found <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Analytic_Hierarchy_Process/More_Hier=
archies" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Talk:Analytic Hierarchy Process/Mor=
e Hierarchies">on a special talk page for this article</a>.
</p><p>The design of any AHP hierarchy will depend not only on the nature o=
f the problem at hand, but also on the knowledge, judgments, values, opinio=
ns, needs, wants, etc. of the participants in the decision-making process. =
Constructing a hierarchy typically involves significant discussion, researc=
h, and discovery by those involved. Even after its initial construction, it=
 can be changed to accommodate newly-thought-of criteria or criteria not or=
iginally considered to be important; alternatives can also be added, delete=
d, or changed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DMFL_25-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-DMFL-25=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>To better understand AHP hierarchies, consider a decision problem wi=
th a goal to be reached, three alternative ways of reaching the goal, and f=
our criteria against which the alternatives need to be measured.
</p><p>Such a hierarchy can be visualized as a diagram like the one immedia=
tely below, with the goal at the top, the three alternatives at the bottom,=
 and the four criteria in between. There are useful terms for describing th=
e parts of such diagrams: Each box is called a node. A node that is connect=
ed to one or more nodes in a level below it is called a parent node. The no=
des to which it is so connected are called its children.
</p><p>Applying these definitions to the diagram below, the goal is the par=
ent of the four criteria, and the four criteria are children of the goal. E=
ach criterion is a parent of the three Alternatives. Note that there are on=
ly three Alternatives, but in the diagram, each of them is repeated under e=
ach of its parents.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AHPHierarchy3.0.png" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52=
/AHPHierarchy3.0.png/250px-AHPHierarchy3.0.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"70" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1141" data=
-file-height=3D"319"></a><figcaption>A simple AHP hierarchy. There are thre=
e Alternatives for reaching the Goal, and four Criteria to be used in decid=
ing among them.</figcaption></figure>
<p>To reduce the size of the drawing required, it is common to represent AH=
P hierarchies as shown in the diagram below, with only one node for each al=
ternative, and with multiple lines connecting the alternatives and the crit=
eria that apply to them. To avoid clutter, these lines are sometimes omitte=
d or reduced in number. Regardless of any such simplifications in the diagr=
am, in the actual hierarchy each criterion is individually connected to the=
 alternatives. The lines may be thought of as being directed downward from =
the parent in one level to its children in the level below.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AHPHierarchy1Labeled.png" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb=
/d/db/AHPHierarchy1Labeled.png/250px-AHPHierarchy1Labeled.png" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"250" height=3D"153" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"591" data-file-height=3D"361"></a><figcaption>AHP hierarchy for choos=
ing a leader. There is one goal, three candidates and four criteria for cho=
osing among them.</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Evaluate_the_hierarchy">Eva=
luate the hierarchy</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=
=3D"Edit section: Evaluate the hierarchy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Once the hierarchy has been constructed, the participants analyze it thr=
ough a series of pairwise comparisons that derive numerical scales of measu=
rement for the nodes. The criteria are pairwise compared against the goal f=
or importance. The alternatives are pairwise compared against each of the c=
riteria for preference. The comparisons are processed mathematically, and p=
riorities are derived for each node.
</p><p>Consider the "Choose a Leader" example above. An important task of t=
he decision makers is to determine the weight to be given each criterion in=
 making the choice of a leader. Another important task is to determine the =
weight to be given to each candidate with regard to each of the criteria. T=
he AHP not only lets them do that, but it lets them put a meaningful and ob=
jective numerical value on each of the four criteria.
</p><p>Unlike most surveys which adopt the five point <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likert_scale" title=3D"Likert scale">Likert scale</a>, =
AHP's questionnaire is 9 to 1 to 9.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cit=
e_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Establish_priorities">Estab=
lish priorities</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"=
Edit section: Establish priorities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This section explains priorities, shows how they are established, and pr=
ovides a simple example.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Priorities_defined_and_expl=
ained">Priorities defined and explained</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Priorities defined and explained"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>Priorities are numbers associated with the nodes of an AHP hierarchy. Th=
ey represent the relative weights of the nodes in any group.
</p><p>Like probabilities, priorities are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dimensionless_quantity" title=3D"Dimensionless quantity">absolute n=
umbers</a> between zero and one, without units or dimensions. A node with p=
riority .200 has twice the weight in reaching the goal as one with priority=
 .100, ten times the weight of one with priority .020, and so forth. Depend=
ing on the problem at hand, "weight" can refer to importance, or preference=
, or likelihood, or whatever factor is being considered by the decision mak=
ers.
</p><p>Priorities are distributed over a hierarchy according to its archite=
cture, and their values depend on the information entered by users of the p=
rocess. Priorities of the Goal, the Criteria, and the Alternatives are inti=
mately related, but need to be considered separately.
</p><p>By definition, the priority of the Goal is 1.000. The priorities of =
the alternatives always add up to 1.000. Things can become complicated with=
 multiple levels of Criteria, but if there is only one level, their priorit=
ies also add to 1.000. All this is illustrated by the priorities in the exa=
mple below.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AHPHierarchy1.1.png" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60=
/AHPHierarchy1.1.png/250px-AHPHierarchy1.1.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"170" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"625" data=
-file-height=3D"424"></a><figcaption>Simple AHP hierarchy with associated d=
efault priorities</figcaption></figure>
<p>Observe that the priorities on each level of the example=E2=80=94the goa=
l, the criteria, and the alternatives=E2=80=94all add up to 1.000.
</p><p>The priorities shown are those that exist before any information has=
 been entered about weights of the criteria or alternatives, so the priorit=
ies within each level are all equal. They are called the hierarchy's defaul=
t priorities. If a fifth Criterion were added to this hierarchy, the defaul=
t priority for each Criterion would be .200. If there were only two Alterna=
tives, each would have a default priority of .500.
</p><p>Two additional concepts apply when a hierarchy has more than one lev=
el of criteria: local priorities and global priorities. Consider the hierar=
chy shown below, which has several Subcriteria under each Criterion.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AHPHierarchy4.0.png" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0=
/AHPHierarchy4.0.png/250px-AHPHierarchy4.0.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"120" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"743" data=
-file-height=3D"358"></a><figcaption>A more complex AHP hierarchy, with loc=
al and global default priorities. In the interest of clarity, the decision =
alternatives do not appear in the diagram.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The local priorities, shown in gray, represent the relative weights of t=
he nodes within a group of siblings with respect to their parent. The local=
 priorities of each group of Criteria and their sibling Subcriteria add up =
to 1.000. The global priorities, shown in black, are obtained by multiplyin=
g the local priorities of the siblings by their parent's global priority. T=
he global priorities for all the subcriteria in the level add up to 1.000.
</p><p>The rule is this: Within a hierarchy, the global priorities of child=
 nodes always add up to the global priority of their parent. Within a group=
 of children, the local priorities add up to 1.000.
</p><p>So far, we have looked only at default priorities. As the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytical_hierarchy" title=3D"Analytical hi=
erarchy">Analytical Hierarchy</a> Process moves forward, the priorities wil=
l change from their default values as the decision makers input information=
 about the importance of the various nodes. They do this by making a series=
 of pairwise comparisons.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Practical_examples">Practic=
al examples</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Analytic_hierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Practical examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Experienced practitioners know that the best way to understand the AHP i=
s to work through cases and examples. Two detailed <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Case_study" title=3D"Case study">case studies</a>, specifi=
cally designed as in-depth teaching examples, are provided as appendices to=
 this article:
</p>
<ul><li>Simple step-by-step example with four Criteria and three Alternativ=
es: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_hierar=
chy_process_%E2%80%94_Leader_example&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" cla=
ss=3D"new" title=3D"Analytic hierarchy process =E2=80=94 Leader example (pa=
ge does not exist)">Choosing a leader for an organization</a>.</li>
<li>More complex step-by-step example with ten Criteria/Subcriteria and six=
 Alternatives: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_=
process_%E2%80%94_Car_example" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Analytic hier=
archy process =E2=80=94 Car example">Buying a family car</a> and Machinery =
Selection Example.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-29"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li></ul>
<p>Some of the books on AHP contain practical examples of its use, though t=
hey are not typically intended to be step-by-step learning aids.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-DMFL_25-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-DMFL-25"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-SaatyFundamentals_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-SaatyFundamentals-30=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> One of them contains a handful of expanded examples, plus abo=
ut 400 AHP hierarchies briefly described and illustrated with figures.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Hierarchon_27-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-Hierarchon-27"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Many examples are discussed, mostly for professional audiences, in p=
apers published by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internation=
al_Symposium_on_the_Analytic_Hierarchy_Process" title=3D"International Symp=
osium on the Analytic Hierarchy Process">International Symposium on the Ana=
lytic Hierarchy Process</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-=
31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-32"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
nalytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hiera=
rchy_process#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Criticisms">Criticisms</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_hierarc=
hy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Criti=
cisms"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>The AHP is included in most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ope=
rations_research" title=3D"Operations research">operations research</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Management_science" title=3D"Mana=
gement science">management science</a> textbooks, and is taught in numerous=
 universities; it is used extensively in organizations that have carefully =
investigated its theoretical underpinnings.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FormanGass_1=
-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_h=
ierarchy_process#cite_note-FormanGass-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The method does have it=
s critics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSDN_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-MSDN-7"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>=20
In the early 1990s a series of debates between critics and proponents of AH=
P was published in <i>Management Science</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_=
process#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_=
note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-38"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <=
i>The Journal of the Operational Research Society,</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hi=
erarchy_process#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_proce=
ss#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-=
42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> two prestigious journals where Saaty and his colleagues had=
 considerable influence. These debates seem to have been settled in favor o=
f AHP:=20
</p>
<ul><li>An in-depth paper was published in <i>Operations Research</i> in 20=
01.</li>
<li>A  2008 <i>Management Science</i> paper reviewing 15 years of progress =
in all areas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple-criteria_=
decision_analysis" title=3D"Multiple-criteria decision analysis">Multicrite=
ria Decision Making</a></li>
<li>in 2008, the major society for operations research, the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_for_Operations_Research_and_the_Managem=
ent_Sciences" title=3D"Institute for Operations Research and the Management=
 Sciences">Institute for Operations Research and the Management Sciences</a=
> formally recognized AHP's broad impact on its fields.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_h=
ierarchy_process#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>A 1997 paper examined possible flaws in the verbal (vs. numerical) scale=
 often used in AHP pairwise comparisons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_proces=
s#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Another from the same year claimed that innocuo=
us changes to the AHP model can introduce order where no order exists.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A 2006 paper foun=
d that the addition of criteria for which all alternatives perform equally =
can alter the priorities of alternatives.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_proce=
ss#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2021, the first comprehensive evaluation of the AHP was published=
 in a book authored by two academics from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Technical_University_of_Valencia" title=3D"Technical University of =
Valencia">Technical University of Valencia</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Universidad_Polit%C3%A9cnica_de_Cartagena" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Universidad Polit=C3=A9cnica de Cartagena">Universidad Poli=
t=C3=A9cnica de Cartagena</a>, and published by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Springer_Nature" title=3D"Springer Nature">Springer Nature</a=
>. Based on an empirical investigation and objective testimonies by 101 res=
earchers, the study found at least 30 flaws in the AHP and found it unsuita=
ble for complex problems, and in certain situations even for small problems=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Rank_reversal">Rank reversa=
l</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_h=
ierarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Rank reversal"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Decision making involves ranking alternatives in terms of criteria or at=
tributes of those alternatives. It is an axiom of some decision theories th=
at when new alternatives are added to a decision problem, the ranking of th=
e old alternatives must not change =E2=80=94 that "<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rank_reversals_in_decision-making" title=3D"Rank reversals=
 in decision-making">rank reversal</a>" must not occur.
</p><p>There are two schools of thought about rank reversal. One maintains =
that new alternatives that introduce no additional attributes should not ca=
use rank reversal under any circumstances. The other maintains that there a=
re some situations in which rank reversal can reasonably be expected. The o=
riginal formulation of AHP allowed rank reversals. In 1993, Forman<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> introduced a second=
 AHP synthesis mode, called the ideal synthesis mode, to address choice sit=
uations in which the addition or removal of an 'irrelevant' alternative sho=
uld not and will not cause a change in the ranks of existing alternatives. =
The current version of the AHP can accommodate both these schools=E2=80=94i=
ts ideal mode preserves rank, while its distributive mode allows the ranks =
to change. Either mode is selected according to the problem at hand.
</p><p>Rank reversal and AHP are extensively discussed in a 2001 paper in <=
i>Operations Research</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FormanGass_1-4" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#=
cite_note-FormanGass-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as well as a chapter entitled <i>Rank =
Preservation and Reversal</i>, in the current basic book on AHP.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-SaatyFundamentals_30-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-SaatyFundamentals-3=
0"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The latter presents published examples of rank reversal due =
to adding copies and near copies of an alternative, due to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transitive_relation" title=3D"Transitive relation"=
>intransitivity</a> of decision rules, due to adding phantom and decoy alte=
rnatives, and due to the switching phenomenon in utility functions. It also=
 discusses the Distributive and Ideal Modes of AHP.
</p><p>A new form of rank reversal of AHP was found in 2014<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analyt=
ic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in which AHP produces rank o=
rder reversal when eliminating irrelevant data, this is data that do not di=
fferentiate alternatives.
</p><p>There are different types of rank reversals.  Also, other methods be=
sides the AHP may exhibit such rank reversals.  More discussion on rank rev=
ersals with the AHP and other MCDM methods is provided in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_reversals_in_decision-making" title=3D"Ran=
k reversals in decision-making">rank reversals in decision-making</a> page.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Non-monotonicity_of_some_we=
ight_extraction_methods">Non-monotonicity of some weight extraction methods=
</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAnalytic_hi=
erarchy_process&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: =
Non-monotonicity of some weight extraction methods"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Within a comparison matrix one may replace a judgement with a less favor=
able judgment and then check to see if the indication of the new priority b=
ecomes less favorable than the original priority. In the context of tournam=
ent matrices, it has been proven by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Oskar_Perron" title=3D"Oskar Perron">Oskar Perron</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
LandauEdmund_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_process#cite_note-LandauEdmund-50"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> that=
 the principal right eigenvector method is not monotonic. This behaviour ca=
n also be demonstrated for reciprocal n x n matrices, where n &gt; 3. Alter=
native approaches are discussed elsewhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Zermelo_51-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hier=
archy_process#cite_note-Zermelo-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hasse_52=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_h=
ierarchy_process#cite_note-Hasse-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_53-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hie=
rarchy_process#cite_note-:0-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_hierarchy_pro=
cess#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
